[Ceara, a state in northeastern Brazil, has a mountainous interior and a long Atlantic coastline lined with dramatic red cliffs. Fortaleza, the capital, is known for its beaches, sprawling Coco Ecological Park, on the Coco River, and the Praia de Iracema neighborhood of bars and restaurants. The Tourism Center is a former 19th-century jail with craft shops in the cells. Area: 148 826 square km. Capital: Fortaleza, Population: 8.843 million (as of 1 Jul 2014); Gross domestic product: 84.36 billion BRL [USD 23.5 billion] (2011).

Minas Gerais, with an area of 588 383 square km (a little bigger than France), is the 3rd largest Brazilian state (after Amazonas and Para); with nearly 18 million people, it is the 2nd most populated state (after Sao Paulo). The capital is Belo Horizonte (which translates as "Beautiful Horizon"); the metropolitan area of Belo Horizonte contains much of the industry of the state. The name Minas Gerais ("General Mines," or "Large Mines") is a reference to the fact that during the 18th and 19th centuries, large mines of gold and precious stones were found in the state. - Mod.CP

