[3] Mongolia, Philippines, Viet Nam
Date: 24 Aug 2015
Source: Outbreak News Today [abridged, edited]
http://outbreaknewstoday.com/measles-in-asia-mongolia-cases-way-up-philippines-and-vietnam-down-significantly-37715/


The number of measles cases in the Western Pacific Region of the World Health Organization as a whole is down significantly through the 1st 6 months of 2015 compared to the same period last year [2014]. The latest data from the UN health agency shows that this area of the Asian-Pacific region has seen a decrease in measles cases from nearly 141 000 cases from 1 Jan-30 Jun 2014 to just 104 000 for the same period this year [2015].

Some countries have seen little difference from 2014 to 2015, like China (83 205 vs 79 499), whereas other countries have seen huge differences.

The one nation that has seen a huge increase in measles this year [2015] is Mongolia. During the 1st 6 months of 2014, they reported a mere 86 cases. Contrast this to the same period in 2015, when Mongolia reported 17 580 cases, up from approximately 3000 cases reported on 31 May 2015.

This comes just a year after Mongolia was one of 4 Western Pacific countries to earn the distinction of being declared measles-free. The Measles Elimination Verification Certificate from the WHO Western Pacific Regional Office requires a case-free streak of 3 years. It has been 5 years since Mongolia reported a measles outbreak. A Mongolian media report in June [2015] described the beginning of the current outbreak.

The 1st case of measles in this recent outbreak was reported on 18 Mar 2015. 13 days later, when the Ministry of Health held a press conference, there had been 333 suspected and 95 confirmed cases, 22 of which were diagnosed in adults. Noting that this particular strain matches a strain identified in China, the Deputy Minister of Health said, after a pause: "Even a few doctors and hospital staff contracted the disease. Apparently, vaccinated people, children and adults alike, can get it, provided they have weak immunity and other chronic illness. What's worse, because we hadn't had an outbreak of measles in 5 years, the doctors in the health facilities were not accustomed to it. Added to all that is the fact that this is an airborne disease, which meant the outbreak would be quite costly."

The press conference ended with the Ministry of Health promising a nation-wide vaccination between from 15-25 May 2015, with help from the WHO regional office and UNICEF.

Other countries reporting big differences, fortunately in the opposite direction, include the Philippines and Viet Nam. The Philippines reported more than 40 000 measles cases during this period in 2014, while seeing only 2231 cases this year [2015]. Likewise, Viet Nam reported nearly 11 000 cases last year [2014] and only 888 so far this year.

