[4] Australia (St Lucia, Brisbane)
Date: 23 Aug 2015
Source: Perth Now APP report [abridged, edited]
http://www.perthnow.com.au/news/breaking-news/qld-uni-measles-alert-spreads-to-toowoomba/story-fnhrvfuw-1227494996127>


A 6th person has contracted measles after an outbreak at Queensland's largest university, prompting the authorities to issue a health alert in a town more than 100 km away. A vaccination centre has been set up at the University of Queensland's St Lucia campus in Brisbane following a spate of measles cases this month [August 2015].

Queensland Health says the latest person to have contracted the highly-contagious disease on campus travelled to Toowoomba, west of Brisbane, last weekend. The infected person visited the Spotted Cow Hotel on Saturday [22 Aug 2015] night and had breakfast at Sizzler on Sunday morning.

Darling Downs Public Health Unit Director Dr Penny Hutchinson said management at both establishments had been advised of the case so they could let staff and customers know. There was potential for more cases to arise in Toowoomba from people who visited those locations, but there's no ongoing risk at either site, she said.

Dr Hutchinson urged Toowoomba residents to be alert for measles symptoms. "Symptoms usually start around 10 days, but can occur between 7 and 18 days after contact with an infectious person," Dr Hutchinson said. "This means that we could expect to see further disease cases from contact with this individual up until around 5 Sep 2015. Measles is one of the most infectious of all communicable diseases and is spread by tiny droplets through coughing and sneezing."

Measles is a viral infection that causes a fever, cough, runny nose and then a red spotty rash and sore eyes a few days later. People with symptoms should stay home and contact their GP for advice, Dr Hutchinson said.

